<center><table border=0><tr><td><center><H2><font face=arial>Re: What?</font></H2></center>
<font face=arial size=2><b>Posted By:</b> <A HREF="/cgi-local/whois2.cgi?Koss">Koss</a><br>
<b>Posted On:</b> 11:01 p.m. 9/2/1999<br>
<b>Subject:</b> Re: What?<p>
<br><center><img src="http://www.everworld.net/pvpquest/images/divider.gif" width=452 height=22 border=0></center><BR><P ALIGN=CENTER><b>In Reply To:</b> <A HREF="http://www.everworld.net/cgi-local/pvp.cgi?read=506" TARGET=_self>What?</A> (The RealmWeaver)
</STRONG><FONT SIZE=2 color=#FFFFFF FACE=arial>
<P>Oh RealmWeaver :P

<P>You cant just say "Oh, well just pay attention!" or "Just use ignore!" to problems that do exist. They tried that in UO, OSI made it sound so simple, "Just do not attack anyone and you wont have to worry about it". The system was a total failure, and there is no way to perfect it. It sounded like a good idea (and still does) but when you put it into action it just does not and will not work.
<P>If there is a problem with the PVP switch, the solution is NOT a modified UO reputation/guard system. That is just crazy, it did not work in UO and it will not work in EQ. The PVP switch is better by far than having to worry about what your current criminal status is, what your reputation is, whether or not this guard is going to kill you if you do this, etc etc etc.
<P>Again, You can not cover every "criminal act" in an online gaming environment. You make the list simple by just saying, "Don't attack, Don't steal, Don't cast spells", but there is more to it. You truly need a "smart AI" to differ between each and every event. You CAN NOT set down a *simple* set of rules for 100,000 people and have them apply to every situation (which it has to do!). The actions that flag you criminal and the ones that don't are basically laws. Even US laws, which have taken over 200 years to develop, still require human intervention and interpretation for each and every case in which they occur. You cant possible program this into a game and have it all run smoothly.
<P>The UO reputation system really was terrible, and no matter how many ways or excuses you come up to deal with it, it will never work.
<P>I am sorry to come down so hard on your ideas but I lived through that mess in UO and even discussion of putting such a similar system into EQ prompts a huge response from me.
<P>Koss
<P>Really sorry I made so many spam posts, never intended this to get so drawn out. I'll stop with this post. Sorry ;)
</FONT></td></tr></table></P>
